posts.name: yadin
posts.cooked:
So after having some issues with our cube ground intake in ISR district 2 , our first proirity was fixing the intake for ISR 3 . first thing after coming back to the shop, we go to run some tests on the intake to figure out the problem exactly. Only problem was…It worked. perfectly too, Even better than it did before comp. And we have absolutely no idea why. No changes were made to the robot or the intake. The robot was exactly as it was at comp.

our intake setup looks like this: (excuse me for the bad drawing but it’s 2:20am and I’m too lazy to find good pictures right now) I don’t have any videos but before it started working we had a problem where the cube would just kinda spin on the bumper instead of go into the robot, or sometimes it wouldn’t even do that and just get pushed away by the front roller.

We desperetly tried to make it not work again: tried it on different curpets, tried over AND under inflating the cubes, we even tried every possible bumper combination since they are not all identical. It kept working.

For now we decided not to make any changes since it works as-is, but the only thing that worries me is that if it can just randomely start working it can do the opposite too.

Has anyone experienced this in the past? if you know what might possibly cause this, it will help alot.

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked:
It is almost certainly your compression and the downward force you are applying on your intake.  You can see the intake trying to pull the cube in but bouncing on it.  The cubes at competition are likely to be dirty and used far more than what you have at your shop.  They are likely not nearly as ‘sticky’, and you intake is struggling to get them into the small gap between your intake and bumper.

You’d have to do the math, but an easy fix might be to remove the bumper section if you don’t want to redo your intake.
